1 1. “Certified community health worker” means a community health
2 worker to whom the State Department of Health has issued a
3 certificate to practice as a certified community health worker in
4 this state;
5 2. “Community health worker” means a frontline health worker
6 who has a shared understanding of and is a trusted member of the
7 community being served; and
8 3. “Department” means the State Department of Health.
9 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2063c of Title 63, unless there
11 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 A. The State Department of Health shall establish a certificate
13 for community health workers. This certification shall be
14 voluntary.
15 B. A certified community health worker may:
16 1. Serve as a liaison between health and social services and
17 the community to facilitate access to services, to improve the
18 quality of service delivery, and to maximize the efficiency of
19 service delivery by coordinating available resources and leveraging
20 partnerships with private, nonprofit, or faith-based organizations;
21 2. Assist individuals in attaining employment, education,
22 occupational training, or other means of supporting employment and
23 promoting self-sufficiency;
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 424 Page 2

1 3. Assist in identifying and communicating gaps in current
2 community and health care resources; and
3 4. Build individual and community capacity by increasing health
4 knowledge and self-sufficiency through a range of activities such as
5 outreach, community education, coaching, mentoring, social support,
6 and advocacy, including efforts within faith-based settings.
7 C. In carrying out the functions described in paragraph 1 of
8 subsection B of this section, community health workers shall
9 emphasize available resources of private, nonprofit, or faith-based
10 organizations, and shall not rely solely on public assistance
11 programs for delivery of services.
12 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
13 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2063d of Title 63, unless there
14 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
15 To be eligible for voluntary community health worker
16 certification, an individual shall:
17 1. Be a United States citizen or lawful permanent resident;
18 2. Be a resident of this state;
19 3. Be at least eighteen (18) years of age; and
20 4. Meet the minimum qualifications for certification
21 promulgated by the State Commissioner of Health under Section 5 of
22 this act.
